# Apply config changes to the running stack

After ANY edit to `config/config.yaml`, run the helper script to propagate
the change. A plain `docker compose restart` is NOT enough.

## Run this command

```bash
./scripts/apply_config.sh
```

## Why

`config/config.yaml` is baked into 4 service images at build time
(`config-service`, `exchange-service`, `mcp-service`, `web-dashboard-service`).
Colima on this host cannot bind-mount the host path (mounts list is empty and
the project path contains a space — `/Volumes/OWC Volume/...`).

So host edits do NOT reach the running containers without a rebuild. The
helper script does the full cycle:

1. Rebuilds the 4 baked-config images
2. Recreates those containers
3. Waits for `config-service` health and POSTs `/api/v1/config/reload`
4. Restarts `strategy-service` and `orchestrator-service` to flush their
   in-memory config caches (they cache config from their first HTTP fetch
   at startup)
5. Prints the live `macd_momentum` parameters as verification

## What NOT to do

- Do NOT only run `docker compose restart` — the baked images keep serving
  old values.
- Do NOT only rebuild `config-service` — `strategy-service` will still hold
  its cached dict until restarted.

## Verifying

After the script finishes, confirm new values in live logs:

```bash
docker compose logs --since 30s strategy-service | grep -E 'lookback=|threshold=|applied overrides'
```
